    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Bargains on the Web</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Alan L Light letter says Thomas L Friedman may be right about Internet backlash (May 30 Op-Ed column), but there is a big advantage in online shopping</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Thomas L. Friedman may be right about Internet backlash (column, May 30), but there is a big advantage to online shopping: price.</p>
        <p>I recently visited a discount electronics store at my local mall to buy a high-end DVD player with a list price of $799. The store's price was $699. Not bad, but just a few clicks on my computer found a price of $469 with free shipping, and no sales tax.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Thomas L. Friedman may be right about Internet backlash (column, May 30), but there is a big advantage to online shopping: price.</p>
        <p>I recently visited a discount electronics store at my local mall to buy a high-end DVD player with a list price of $799. The store's price was $699. Not bad, but just a few clicks on my computer found a price of $469 with free shipping, and no sales tax.</p>
        <p>How can stores, with their high overhead costs, ever compete?</p>
        <p>ALAN L. LIGHT  Iowa City, May 30, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
